<h3 id="fitting-the-pins">Fitting the pins</h3>

<p>Cutting the pins is conceptually the same, except the layout is based on the already cut tails (as opposed to whatever looks good). A little gappy but not the worst for a second box (fifth corner), and it will be much improved when glue expands the wood and the gaps are filled with sawdust. The gap on the bottom tail / pin is from the drawer bottom groove. You could avoid this by having a wider tail or just construct the drawer with a different type of bottom, but this works for me.</p>

<p><img src="/assets/images/dresser/26.jpg" class="img-fluid" /></p>

<h3 id="moxon-vise">Moxon vise</h3>

<p>One reason why it’s been a while since the last update is that I changed up my woodworking space; instead of working in between two parked cars, I’ve dedicated one corner of the garage to woodworking. For now the workbench is a sort of temporary Fraken-bench, but one fixture that has dramatically improved the ergonomics (and thus my speed and accuracy) is this Moxon styled vise. The jaws are reclaimed white oak which were previously chair rails at a middle school. Instead of buying dedicated hardware I opted for some spare bar clamps I had laying around. The vise raises the work higher off the bench so sighting and sawing is much easier. Now that I have a dedicated space, a better workbench is in order… Stay tuned!</p>

